        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" resp="#NW">
                  <div type="textpart" n="1" subtype="ogham" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down" /><persName><name>ᚒᚇᚄᚐᚌᚉᚔ</name></persName> 
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><persName><name>ᚒᚂᚉᚐᚌᚅᚔ</name></persName>  
                </ab>
            </div>
                 <div type="textpart" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam">
                 <ab>
                     <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down"/><persName><name>UDSAGCI</name></persName>
                     <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><persName><name>ULCAGNI</name></persName>
                 </ab>
                 </div>
                <div type="textpart" n="2" subtype="latin" xml:lang="la-Latn">
                    <ab>
                        <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down"/><w><supplied reason="lost">HI</supplied>C</w> <w>IACIT</w> <persName><name>VLCAGNI</name></persName>
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
                    <note>For the inscription on the left the ogham carver attempted ULCAGNI but put the 2 strokes of L to the left rather than right of the arris. Having gone wrong at the outset, knowing the following letter comes from a different aicme, it was put on the opposite (wrong) side, as was the other ‘sided’ consonant. What was written is UDSAGQI. Having got to the end and having realised the mistake, however, the name was re-carved on the opposite side, this time getting the placement correct: ULCAGNI. This is the second south-west ogham with a spelling error. The same mistake was made at Fardel 30 miles away.</note>
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Latin: "here lies Ólcan"</p>
                <note>The same name is found about 23 miles away at Nanscow (VLCAGNI FILI | SEVERI) and Ballyhank, Co. Cork (I-COR-049; CIIC 100). It means something like ‘little bad guy’ (Ziegler 1994, 241), and seems to be common among religious men (David Stifter pers. com.). It has been suggested that he too was an ecclesiastic, but it is advisable to be cautious about such an assumption – there are three examples from Anglesey of the same formula (i.e. personal name in genitive with ‘hic iacit’). </note>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The palaeography of the Latin inscription suggests a date in the 5th century.</p>
            </div>
